HTML Attributes: title, id, class
What Are Attributes?
--Attributes in HTML provide additional information about elements. They're always included inside the opening tag.

1. title Attribute
--Shows a tooltip when you hover over the element.
<p title="This is a tooltip!">Hover over this text to see the title.</p>

2. id Attribute
--A unique identifier for an element.
--Used for styling, JavaScript, or linking.
<p id="intro">This is an introduction paragraph.</p>

You can style this in CSS like:
<style>
  #intro {
    color: blue;
  }
</style>

3. class Attribute
--Used to define a group of elements with the same style.
<p class="highlight">This is a highlighted paragraph.</p>
<p class="highlight">This one is also highlighted.</p>

Style using CSS:
<style>
  .highlight {
    background-color: yellow;
  }
</style>

Full Example Code:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Day 13: HTML Attributes</title>
  <style>
    #intro {
      color: green;
      font-weight: bold;
    }
    .highlight {
      background-color: #fffa9c;
      padding: 5px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Day 13: HTML Attributes</h1>
  <p title="Hover to see this tooltip!">Hover your mouse over this paragraph.</p>
  <p id="intro">This paragraph has a unique ID and is styled differently.</p>
  <p class="highlight">This paragraph is highlighted using class attribute.</p>
  <p class="highlight">This is another highlighted paragraph.</p>
</body>
</html>

Summary:
| Attribute | Use Case                                            |
| --------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| `title`   | Shows tooltip on hover                              |
| `id`      | Uniquely identifies one element                     |
| `class`   | Applies same style or behavior to multiple elements |
